router

### Description

Currently, If I want to provide a Store service on my route providers, I cannot get the route details for that route. In the example below, inside the UserDetailsStore I cannot get the ongoing navigation's ActivatedRouteSnapshot in order to use it for data fetching for example.

```ts
{
  path: 'user/:id',
  providers: [UserDetailsStore],
  component: Child,
  resolve: {
    loader: () => {
      inject(UserDetailsStore).loadUserDetails();
      return true;
    },
  },
},


@Injectable()
export class UserDetailsStore {
  someRouteData = inject(SOME_ROUTER_PROVIDED_TOKEN_FOR_THE_ROUTE);

  user = signal<{ id: string } | null>(null);

  loadUserDetails() {
    const id = this.someRouteData.paramMap.get('id')!;

    // fetch user data

    // set user
    this.user.set({ id });
  }
}
```

### Proposed solution
Provide access to ongoing navigation’s ActivatedRouteSnapshot on the route providers through some DI token.

### Alternatives considered

Passing the ActivatedRouteSnapshot around. 

```ts
{
  path: 'user/:id',
  providers: [UserDetailsStore],
  component: Child,
  resolve: {
    loader: (snapshot: ActivatedRouteSnapshot) => {
      inject(UserDetailsStore).loadUserDetails(snapshot);
      return true;
    },
  },
},


@Injectable()
export class UserDetailsStore {
  user = signal<{ id: string } | null>(null);

  loadUserDetails(snapshot: ActivatedRouteSnapshot) {
    const id = snapshot.paramMap.get('id')!;

    // fetch user data

    // set user
    this.user.set({ id });
  }
}
```

Moves tokens out of `core/tokens` and into their respective component directories.

Also uses a new `token-utils.slot()` function that replaces `create-tokens-slot`:

```
// Before:
.mat-comp {
  @include token-utils.create-token-slot(border-radius, container-shape);
}

// After:
.mat-comp {
  border-radius: token-utils.slot(container-shape);
}
```
